Correlation rules

This must be very strict.

Each workflow run needs a stable correlation id shared across:

controller release handling
plan generation
node-agent execution
installer substeps
final installed-state publication

Without that, you will end up with fragments instead of a workflow.

Recommended correlation seed:

{release_kind}/{component_name}/{node_id}/{plan_generation}
or a generated workflow id written into plan metadata and reused by node-agent

Best option:

controller creates workflow run id
includes run id / correlation id in plan metadata
node-agent reuses it
installer receives it through context

That gives you one continuous story.

Important design rules
1. Workflow service is the canonical source

Do not let admin scrape state from many services directly for this feature.

2. Use gRPC and proto messages as the contract

The workflow model should be shared cleanly across backend components.

3. Store structured state, not just raw logs

Logs are supplemental evidence, not the workflow model itself.

4. Emphasize actor handoff

The workflow representation must make it obvious where responsibility moved from controller to node-agent to installer to runtime.

5. Keep history

The whole point is to stop losing the story after the current failure is over.

